            <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/section/recess/culture">CULTURE</a></span></div>

                <h1>We asked you for bite-size stories about love. Here’s what you told us.</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/a5e35971-096c-498d-9f4c-fdaae362a6fd.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="" class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            

                                                             <aside class="photo-caption photo-credit d-block pl-1">
                                    <figcaption class="d-block">
                                                                                    Photo by <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/hannah-miao">Hannah Miao</a> |
                                                                                                                                The Chronicle
                                                                            </figcaption>
                                </aside>
                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/hannah-miao">Hannah Miao</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">November 13, 2019 | 1:18pm EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/11/we-asked-you-for-short-stories-about-love-heres-what-you-told-us" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/11/we-asked-you-for-short-stories-about-love-heres-what-you-told-us&amp;text=We asked you for bite-size stories about love. Here’s what you told us." target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=We%20asked%20you%20for%20bite-size%20stories%20about%20love.%20Here%E2%80%99s%20what%20you%20told%20us.%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2019%2F11%2Fwe-asked-you-for-short-stories-about-love-heres-what-you-told-us" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>In the spirit of The New York Times’ adored <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/column/modern-love" target="_blank">“Modern Love”</a> column, now an <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/11/modern-love-offers-bite-size-rom-coms-to-those-seeking-a-digital-dose-of-feel-good-this-fall" target="_blank">Amazon Prime television show</a>, I invited Duke students and alumni to submit their own “Tiny Love Stories” told in 100 words or less. Here’s what they had to say:</p>
<p><strong>Kissing Under the Milky Way</strong></p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>I discover the cute boy sitting next to me in my Neuro101 discussion is applying to the same DukeEngage program as me. I joke that I might kill him in his sleep to ensure I get a spot in the cohort. Instead, we both get a spot and I fall in love with him. We share our first kiss under the milky way in the middle of the desert. Then, we get married (for a DukeEngage cultural excursion). We were together for about 3 years. I hated Duke often, but I loved it because it brought me him. —<em>Kelsey Graywill, Trinity ‘18</em></p>
<p><br></p>
<!--ceo:replacemode=raw-->




    <figure style="max-width:100%;    " class="embedded-media embedded-image">
        
        <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/0e9d4737-2711-4034-8d25-8f28944e04bd.sized-1000x1000.png?w=1000" class="w-100" alt="" />                    <span class="embedded-credit">
                                    <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/hannah-miao">Hannah Miao</a>                                            </span>
                    </figure>
<p><strong>Opposites Attract</strong></p>
<p>We kissed at a UNC bar — two Duke students alone in a sea of state-school fervor. It was a love story as old as time: Boy meets Girl, Girl talks to Boy, Boy and Girl hit it off. Then, of course, Girl turns out to be a lesbian, Boy is about as gay as one could possibly be, and they kiss in celebration of how little attraction they have for one another. The kiss held as much meaning as any straight kiss, but in the opposite direction. It cemented every desire to find our special someone, just not each other. —<em>Yousuf Rehman, senior</em></p>
<p><br></p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <!--ceo:replacemode=raw-->




    <figure style="max-width:100%;    " class="embedded-media embedded-image">
        
        <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/cfa893eb-ce81-405f-a0a5-9157e6cf4d25.sized-1000x1000.png?w=1000" class="w-100" alt="" />                    <span class="embedded-credit">
                                    <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/hannah-miao">Hannah Miao</a>                                            </span>
                    </figure>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Twin-Size Love</strong></p>
<p>Love used to mean a lack of separation — snuggling under the comforters of a twin-size bed even as another sat less than two feet away. It meant sharing everything from school lunches to winter coats to our circle of friends. What I once thought was “love” was merely proximity. Love is complicated; it is leading separate lives and laughing or crying when we meet in the middle. But it is and always will be you, my twin sister, my inspiration, my safe haven, sitting on your own twin-size bed in your own room hundreds of miles away. —<em>Vivian Yuan, junior</em></p>
                            

